snippet.textDisplay:
I agree with Ford's decision to replace the Sport badge with the ST badge. The ST line is the interim between the base models and the all out performance models. Previously, the Sport and ST badges shared the same space. Sure, the Fusion, Edge, and Explorer Sport models or Taurus SHO don't feel like the nimble little Focus and Fiesta ST, but I wouldn't expect them to. They are still only the middle of the road in performance, though. I think it makes sense for Ford to unify the mid-level performance trims into one. They may not all have the same performance characteristics, but they are more powerful and better handling than the standard trims.

That said, I think Ford needs to be a bit more liberal in their tuning. They are EXTREMELY conservative when tuning those sportier models, which is why the Edge at 9:20 only feels "pretty quick. Heh, I mean..." A mild tune to relax the drive train protection nannies makes a HUGE difference.

Also, the new Explorer ST has the 400hp 3.0L twin turbo that's not available in other trims. It has a stiffer, sport tuned suspension. It's lighter; and it is AWD on a RWD platform. If you ask me, you are mistaken in using a shot of the Explorer ST when referring to the "lows" being low.

snippet.textDisplay: This video really doesn't make that much sense, since you kinda answered all the "Why is that a thing?" questions yourself. M-preformance, amg-line, s-line and st-line are all merely cosmetic packages. They aren't supposed to include performance increases. They're basically just there for the people that don't want/can't afford the full fledged M, AMG, S or ST models but still want their car to look somewhat meaner. Also, quattro last was a performance badge 30 years ago when they made their first AWD cars. But shortly after that it started to just be an idication that the car is AWD. It's not like an Audi 80 Type 85 quattro had that much more performance than a regular Audi 80 Type 85. I agree on the Nismo one tho, that's just redicoulous, at least call it Nismo-package or something to differentiate it from the old Nismos.

snippet.textDisplay:
There's a lot of bad info in this video, particularly regarding M Performance. Is it silly to have an M Performance version of an X2? Yes! But to say it has no power bump over the standard X2 xDrive 28i is incorrect. In fact, it's a significant increase.
Also GR was a terrible example with only less than a handful of models... what, the Supra and European-spec Yaris?
I do think Alfa's QV badge was worth talking about, since it has an actual reason for even being a badge in the first place (if you know the history, you know what I mean...), not to mention being perhaps one of the more interesting ones to talk about. It's even been applied to FWD-based hatchbacks.
This video also lacked mention of a few popular luxury-brand performance monikers, including Jaguar/LR's SVR badge, Lexus's F or F Sport models (the latter of which are, ironically, a perfect example of what you are talking about with M Performance, which incorrectly states there's no power gain), or Volvo's Polestar.
